1.Empirical probability of the 1st type error of a small sample

\[ H_{0}: 2 \mu_{1}-\mu_{2}=0 \]

library("mvtnorm")
library(mixtools)
## mixtools package, version 1.2.0, Released 2020-02-05
## This package is based upon work supported by the National Science Foundation under Grant No. SES-0518772.
## 
## Attaching package: 'mixtools'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:mvtnorm':
## 
##     dmvnorm, rmvnorm
library(OptSig)
n <- 30
mu <-  c(1, 2)
Sigma <- matrix(c(1, 0.5, 0.5, 2),2,2)

set.seed(1234)
sample <- rmvnorm(n, mu, Sigma)
a <- 0
A <- c(2, -1) 
Tvalue <- n * t(A %*% apply(sample, 2, mean) - a) %*% solve(A %*% Sigma %*% A) %*% (A %*% apply(sample, 2, mean) - a)
samplealphachi=1-pchisq(Tvalue,1)
TTvalue <- (n - 1) * t(A %*% apply(sample, 2, mean) - a) %*% solve(A %*% cov(sample) %*% A) %*% (A %*% apply(sample, 2, mean) - a)
samplealphaf=1-pf(TTvalue,1,99)
Tvalue
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.0265073
TTvalue
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.0252195
samplealphachi
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.8706675
samplealphaf
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.8741448
plot(sample,pch=20,xlab="Margin No. 1", ylab="Margin No. 2")
ellipse(mu=mu, sigma=Sigma,alpha = .05, col="red") 
ellipse(mu=mu, sigma=Sigma,alpha = 0.8706675, col="blue") 
ellipse(mu=mu, sigma=Sigma,alpha = 0.8741448, col="green")

As we can see from the diagram above, the results of the two tests are similar for the small sample. The rejection areas are much bigger than the theoretical area.

2.

\[ H_{1}: 2 \mu_{1}-\mu_{2}\neq0 \]

chi-square

n=30
set.seed(1)
sample1 <- rmvnorm(n, mu, Sigma)
a <- 0
A <- c(2, -1) 
Tvalue1 <- n * t(A %*% apply(sample1, 2, mean) - a) %*% solve(A %*% Sigma %*% A) %*% (A %*% apply(sample1, 2, mean) - a)
Tvalue1 
##         [,1]
## [1,] 1.51795
samplealphachi1=1-pchisq(Tvalue1,1)
samplealphachi1
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.2179301
Power.Chisq(df=1,ncp=1.517953,alpha=0.2179301,Figure=TRUE)

In general, test power increases as the sample size increases.
